{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"producer": "Adobe PDF Library 17.0", "creator": "Adobe InDesign 19.5 (Macintosh)", "creationdate": "2025-06-30T13:23:51+01:00", "moddate": "2025-06-30T13:23:54+01:00", "trapped": "/False", "source": "corpus\\autistic-spectrum-v4.pdf", "total_pages": 47, "page": 5, "page_label": "6"}, "page_content": "\u2022 disguise the reasons for their behaviour by taking on a role like the class clown, the \nloner who doesn\u2019t care what anyone thinks, etc.\nSigns of maskers:\n\u2022 Often quiet (but not always!)\n\u2022 Perfectionist tendencies\n\u2022 Reluctant to ask for or access support because they don\u2019t want to appear different\n\u2022 Seem fine at school and then have meltdowns or shutdowns at home\n\u2022 Rehearses conversations and use rehearsed answers\nHow to help your child who is masking:\n\u2022 At home - build in downtime each day where they don\u2019t have to mask. Maybe \ninclude sensory activities or space to focus on their special interests.\n\u2022 Plan out your child\u2019s week based on how much energy they have and how much \nenergy each activity will use up. They are then less likely to burn out.\n\u2022 Work with school to find regular opportunities during the day for your child to \nunmask.\n\u2022 Remind yourself that regular meltdowns or shutdowns after school are a sign your \nchild feels safe enough to drop the mask at home.", "type": "Document"}}